attacker_controls tokens — choose every token that genuinely applies:
  bytes           input file / stream / packet bytes (most parsers, codecs)
  call-sequence   the ATTACKER picks which public API calls run and in what
                  order — a scripting / plugin engine running attacker-supplied
                  scripts, or an RPC/IPC surface exposing the API to attacker
                  requests. NOT a library an application drives in a fixed order
                  over attacker bytes (see guidance).
  timing          timing / scheduling control (browsers, JIT)
  race            concurrent threads or processes (servers, runtimes)
  protocol-state  multi-message protocol state machine (TLS, HTTP, DNS
                  clients and servers)
  env             environment variables / process state (rare: shells)
  fs-state        filesystem layout the attacker shapes (rare: archive
                  and path-handling tools)

Guidance:
- Almost every parser / codec / format library has `bytes`.
- Add `call-sequence` ONLY when the attacker themselves chooses the public API
  call order — a scripting/plugin engine that runs attacker-supplied scripts, or
  an RPC/IPC surface that exposes the API to attacker requests. A fuzz harness
  exploring call orders is a TEST artifact, not an attacker. For a library an
  application drives in a FIXED order over attacker-supplied bytes — most
  parsers, codecs, regex and format libraries — the call order is NOT
  attacker-controlled: use `bytes` only. Do NOT add `call-sequence` just because
  the API is stateful or is fuzzed call-by-call; that conflates the harness with
  the attacker and turns caller-contract/robustness bugs into false security
  reports. (Example: an XML or JSON parser an app calls to parse untrusted bytes
  is `["bytes"]`, even though a callback freed mid-parse can crash it — that
  callback is caller code, not attacker-controlled.)
- Add `protocol-state` for network-protocol implementations.
- Be conservative: never list a token the attacker cannot actually reach.
  Over-claiming turns upstream-robustness bugs into false security reports.

Output a single JSON object (no prose, no fences):
{
  "attacker_controls": ["bytes", "..."],
  "reasoning": "<one short sentence on why these tokens fit the target>"
}

Constraints:
- attacker_controls MUST be a non-empty subset of the tokens listed above.
- Order tokens from most to least obviously attacker-controlled.
